<TEXT>
insider trading on stolen business week stock 
tip columns has alarmed the magazines rivals compelling some to 
review their own security and recheck back issues to make sure they 
havent been victimized too 
we dont take any pleasure in what happened to business week 
but were in the enviable position of bolting the barn door before 
the horse escapes or at least checking the locks said gary 
belis spokesman for fortune which has a biweekly circulation of 
755000 were checking the locks 
belis said a spot check of fortunes companies to watch 
column going back several months showed no unusual prepublication 
activity in any stocks mentioned 
senior editorial officials at forbes and money two other widely 
read business magazines also said they were reassessing protection 
of marketsensitive material in the aftermath of the scandal at 
business week 
in addition the printing companies used by all four magazines 
said they were scrutinizing security and reminding all employees 
that unpublished material is sacrosanct and not to leave the plant 
the scandal surfaced july 21 when business week the nations 
largest business weekly with a circulation of nearly 1 million 
disclosed evidence of possibly illegal trading on stocks featured 
in its inside wall street column before it was available to the 
public 
a major investigation has since revealed workers in two plants 
run by business week printer rr donnelley amp co took copies the 
day before they were released to the public and peddled them to 
brokers sometimes for as little as 20 each 
as of the weekend four donnelley printers and three stock 
brokers one each from merrill lynch amp co prudentialbache 
securities co and advest inc had lost their jobs trades in 
several more brokerages are under investigation for possible links 
to prepublished inside wall street tips 
unlike newspapers where the time gap between writing and 
printing sensitive material is brief weeklies and monthlies face 
the problem of protecting potentially marketmoving items over a 
period of days and weeks 
the problem is compounded in masscirculation magazines which 
rely on printing plants at several locations and the honesty of 
hundreds of printers couriers truckers and postal workers who 
have access before subscribers do 
theres a real limitation on our ability to place guards on 
every truck said landon y jones managing editor of money a 
monthly with a circulation of 18 million 
jones said money sent a letter to its printer world color press 
in effingham ill after the business week scandal surfaced 
warning that the material they handle is property of money 
magazine it is their obligation to protect moneys property as it 
passes through their hands 
he said a check of moneys wall street column and other 
potentially sensitive material going back at least one year found 
no suspicious trading 
at forbes also printed by world color press deputy managing 
editor lawrence minard said the 740000circulation weekly and its 
printer historically have had a firm understanding about 
confidentiality 
nevertheless minard said we did reiterate to world color 
that we expect the agreement weve had with them to be vigilantly 
observed 
minard said there was no effort at forbes to recheck back 
issues but he said i suppose on a continuing basis i very 
unofficially monitor it 
for their part donnelley world color and brown printing co of 
wauseca minn which prints fortune have undertaken security 
crackdowns 
besides dismissing employees implicated in the business week 
scandal chicagobased donnelley has reminded all workers of a ban 
on removing any material from plants others have done likewise 
donnelley also has uniformed sentries at exits plainclothes 
guards patrolling production lines and a policy that workers 
clothing may be searched nevertheless spokesman james ratcliffe 
said the company still must largely rely on employees integrity 
to frisk 650 people would be a bit impractical he said 
