<TEXT>
a fair housing bill the first major expansion 
of civil rights laws in two decades is heading to the white house 
for the signature of president reagan who has endorsed the measure 
the legislation gives federal officials new power to enforce 
fair housing laws and extends antidiscrimination protection to the 
disabled and families with children 
the bill was approved monday by the house with no debate final 
congressional passage came in a nearly deserted chamber as a few 
house members concurred by voice vote in amendments approved last 
week by the senate 
the original fair housing law passed in 1968 after the 
assassination of civil rights leader martin luther king jr gave 
the federal government only a mediation role in settling housing 
disputes 
under the new bill the secretary of housing and urban 
development is empowered to go to court to seek stiff fines against 
property owners accused of discrimination 
current protections against racial and sexual discrimination are 
extended to the handicapped and to families with children under 18 
in addition the bill says new residences with at least four 
units would have to be accessible to the handicapped 
the added protection for families with young children 
effectively ends adults only restrictions except for 
exemptions for retirement communities for the elderly 
</TEXT>
