withdrawal of his proposal to centralize gop authority 
i think the democrats have done a lot of damage to themselves 
with their rules said grace boulton a gop national 
committeewoman from oklahoma who advocated a rival proposal that 
would have given state parties the right to overrule state laws 
governing party procedures 
i just think to have any kind of national committee or group 
approving state party rules is the wrong way to go she said 
dropping the two competing proposals was part of a compromise 
worked out earlier this summer ms boulton said 
republican rules currently require state parties to adhere to 
local laws such as those establishing and scheduling primaries in 
picking their national convention delegates 
moore said the problem with this is there are 36 states where 
we do not control the legislatures and thus democrats are allowed 
to govern what ought to be matters of internal republican party 
policy 
the issue arose during the 1988 election when southern state 
legislatures controlled by democrats decided to hold their 
primaries on one day which became known as super tuesday march 8 
some republican state parties raised objections but were powerless 
to do anything more 
supreme court decisions have said that the parties not the 
states have the final say over their internal operations 
including the selection of delegates to presidential nominating 
conventions 
moore said that under those decisions the national parties 
clearly have the authority to overrule state law but it is unclear 
whether state parties can exercise the same authority 
the supreme court is considering a case dealing with that very 
issue but moore said he did not believe the ruling would go in 
favor of the state parties 
moore said his proposal was not intended to allow the national 
party to meddle in state party affairs but he acknowledged there 
was a fear it would put the gop on the slippery slope to where 
the democrats are 
