<TEXT>
twenty soviet officials today inspected 
a cruise missile base and repair shop under the superpower treaty 
to remove mediumrange nuclear missiles from europe 
the soviet inspectors led by viacheslav s lyebedev arrived 
monday at abelag airport in brussels on a tupolev134 of the soviet 
airline aeroflot they were welcomed by us military and belgian 
officials 
the soviets divided into two teams were driven this morning to 
florennes air base 40 miles south of brussels and a repair 
factory in gosselies 10 miles north of the base 
in florennes which houses the 485th us tactical missile wing 
the united states has deployed 20 cruise missiles since 1985 
including four spares according to the latest figures there were 
55 missiles at the gosselies repair plant which belongs to sabca 
a belgian aviation company servicing us cruise missiles 
under the treaty the inspectors may spend up to 24 hours at 
each site with a possible eighthour extension 
the inspections are part of the intermediaterange nuclear 
forces treaty under which the united states and the soviet uhion 
are to destroy within three years all mediumrange nuclear missiles 
with ranges of between 300 and 3400 miles the treaty gives each 
party onsite inspection rights for 13 years 
under a 1979 nato agreement 572 cruise and pershing 2 missiles 
were to be deployed in five european nations 
soviet inspectors have visited us missile sites and related 
installations in britain west germany the netherlands and the 
united states soviet inspectors have not yet viewed us nuclear 
missiles in italy 
us inspectors have visited nuclear sites in the soviet union 
east germany and czechoslovakia 
