art appraisers stacey roman and phillip 
jelley were in town anyway for an auction of works from two failed 
banks so folks at the anchorage museum of history and art figured 
theyd use their services for a fundraiser 
for a 5 donation to the museum people were invited to bring in 
their family treasures monday and find out from the experts what 
they were really worth there were no major finds and a lot of 
disappointment as the appraisers spent five hours reviewing a host 
of objets dart but a few people learned their pieces were at 
least good buys 
roman said he mostly examined a lot of photo reproductions 
a lot of decorative pieces and said things like it would 
cost you more to get it framed than its worth 
he said he developed the phrase decorative piece because 
its better than telling somebody its a piece of junk just 
because it doesnt have a lot of value doesnt mean it doesnt have 
sentimental value 
roman and jelley work for the californiabased art auction house 
of butterfield amp butterfield and the main purpose of their visit 
is wednesday nights auction of a collection acquired by the 
federal deposit insurance corp as a result of its takeover of two 
failed alaska banks 
the collection includes a huge sydney laurence rendition of 
mount mckinley valued 180000 to 220000 and some other works 
valued at more than 10000 
literally its a treasure hunt roman said he is director 
of the auction houses painting department and his hope was to 
unearth paintings worth shipping to california for sale 
butterfield amp butterfield charges commissions ranging from 35 
percent for items that sell for 100 or less to 10 percent for 
pieces sold for 5000 or more 
basically my job is to look at beautiful things all day 
roman said and every day hope springs anew that someone will pull 
out of a plastic bag some amazing painting thats never been seen 
in 100 years 
but it was not to be monday 
jelley said he saw a nice little rug and a cast bronze bust 
but the only thing perhaps worth shipping to san francisco was a 
silver tea set he plans to research some more 
other items produced included a large parchment page of 
gregorian chant brought back from europe after world war ii whose 
owner believed it dated from the middle ages a hungarian mirror 
painting a religious scene purchased 21 years ago for 20 in a 
budapest antique shop and a sealed bottle of old mr boston 
straight rye whisky from the prohibition era 
the parchment it turned out was probably 19thcentury and not 
worth much 
but the hungarian mirror painting was definitely a good buy it 
would probably bring about 600 at auction jelley told its owner 
who had talked her way past hungarian border guards when they 
questioned whether she should be allowed to take the painting out 
of their country 
the whiskey too had no value at auction because while wine can 
be auctioned off it is against the law to auction hard liquor 
so what are jorene and shield downey going to do with grandmas 
medicinal pint preserved so carefully all these years 
our anniversary is on valentines day mrs downey said 
were going to drink it 
