<TEXT>
a state board today assumed control of the 
citys finances and threatened defiant council members with 
criminal charges in an effort force them to accept a courtordered 
desegregation plan 
in short our goal is to save yonkers from itself said 
secretary of state gail shaffer head of the yonkers emergency 
financial control board the board voted 51 to impose a wage and 
hiring freeze and made council members who refuse to obey rules for 
fiscal responsibility subject to misdemeanor charges 
the four council members who voted against the desegregation 
plan ordered by us district judge leonard sand already are paying 
fines and face a threat of imprisonment beginning thursday on 
sands contempt of court citation 
the us 2nd district court of appeals today said it would rule 
on a city request to stay 500aday fines against the councilmen 
and bankrupting fines against yonkers the panel did not say when 
it would rule 
the control board established by gov mario cuomo earlier in 
the decade when yonkers came near bankruptcy has sweeping powers 
to control the budget of the states fourth largest city it could 
remove the councilmen from office 
city manager neil deluca cast the single negative vote because 
the control board is not strong enough at this time to avert 
fiscal disaster we may have to look to other entities to join me 
in resolving this issue 
mayor nicholas wasiscko who has called a council meeting for 
wednesday night said the only thing that will make any 
difference is the threat of removal from office 
sand fined the city 100 the first day doubling daily so that 
by day 22 the amount would have wiped out the citys 337 million 
budget deluca said the city would begin mass layoffs if the 
situation was not resolved by monday 
sand who in 1985 found the city liable for intentionally 
segregating its schools and housing over 40 years found the city 
and councilmen in contempt last week when the council voted 43 
against a resolution supporting the construction of 800 units of 
affordable housing throughout the city 
michael sculnick attorney for the city asked the appellate 
panel today to put the fines on hold pending a full appeal of 
sands contempt order because if they continued the city will be 
bankrupt in less than two weeks 
lawyers for the councilmen argued that sand had exceeded his 
authority by ordering passage of legislation that would implement 
the housing plan there are limits to a federal courts authority 
even to remedy an unconstitutional action said james d harmon 
attorney for councilman peter chema 
michael sussman attorney for the national assocation for the 
advancement of colored people contended that the appeals court had 
a duty to sand the dignity of the federal court is under 
assault said sussman by a group of citizens who think theyre 
above the law 
deluca who has pinpointed aug 21 as the last day the states 
fourth largest city can pay the price of defiance said if the 
appeals panel denied the stay he would write to sand asking him to 
grant a stay himself and initiate roundtheclock negotiations to 
resolve the crisis 
but deluca said the city has about 66 million cash on hand and 
the last day the city can pay a fine is aug 21 when the daily 
fine is 261 million but the cumulative fine would be 524 
million 
he said he still hoped cuomo would intervene or that one of the 
councilmen would change his vote 
sand had called for the governors assistance noting the 
governors power to remove elected officials cuomo has said he is 
reluctant to do that because it would be complicated and the city 
has appealed the contempt finding 
getting a councilman to change his vote would be difficult too 
because theyre all heroes now said deluca 
the four vice mayor henry spallone nicholas longo chema and 
edward fagan may face additional financial pressure if a citizens 
group goes ahead and files a 100 million civil suit against them 
for negligence dereliction of duty illegal conduct and waste 
thomas dickerson an attorney and vice president of citizens and 
neighbors organized to protect yonkers said the four councilmen 
had violated state law and the city charter by their actions and 
had caused the city irreparable harm publicly and financially 
</TEXT>
