<TEXT>
a federal judge has ordered school officials 
to build a glassfront isolation booth inside a classroom so a 
6yearold who has aids can be taught with other children 
the box to measure at least 6 feet by 8 feet is to have a desk 
and a potty chair a sound system and a fulltime teachers aide 
us district judge elizabeth kovachevich said in her ruling 
monday she took into consideration the concerns of all involved in 
the case brought by the girls adoptive mother rosa martinez 
against the hillsborough county school board last september 
the judge expressed hope that once eliana martinez is able to 
see how her mentally handicapped schoolmates cope she will become 
toilettrained and learn not to habitually place her thumb and 
forefinger in her mouth 
once that happens the remote theoretical possibility that 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome could be spread to her 
classmates will be so slight that she must be allowed to sit in the 
classroom with her peers the judge ruled 
no aids cases have been proven to have been transmitted through 
exposure to urine feces or saliva even though the virus that 
causes the disease has been found in these bodily secretions the 
judge wrote 
steve hanlon elianas lawyer called the judges ruling 
creative and said he hoped that within six weeks of starting 
school aug 29 eliana will have progressed enough to leave the 
booth 
but a school official labeled the chamber idea sadistic and 
compared it to child abuse 
all i can do is see that little face in a bubble very close 
to other children but not able to take part in what the other 
children are doing said marion s rogers a member of the 
hillsborough county school board and a former teacher i think i 
feel that this is as close to child abuse as it can be 
sam rosales head of the classroom teachers association said 
tuesday that teachers who are aware of the ruling have had 
basically a positive attitude although slightly apprehensive 
of the judges decision he said i think she broke new 
ground but its still a middleofthe road ruling 
ms martinez wanted her daughter schooled with other trainable 
mentally handicapped children at manhattan exceptional center 
saying eliana needed the socialization and interaction 
the school district wanted eliana taught at home out of fear she 
could transmit the aids virus the girl has been in home 
instruction since june 1987 
sam rampello vice chairman of the school board said what 
the judge is asking us to do is unusual but were going to do it 
im not criticizing im not praising we have to take all the good 
and all the problems that come with it and all the consequences 
that come with it 
eliana is one of 500 children in a pilot pediatric aids program 
who have been treated with experimental drugs including azt 
kovachevich said elianas case of aids probably contracted from 
transfusions of contaminated blood after her premature birth in 
puerto rico is being held in check by the treatment 
kovachevich presided over the case brought by the three ray 
brothers in arcadia hemophiliacs who doctors believe were exposed 
to the virus through treatment with clotting agents from 
contaminated blood 
she ordered the brothers admitted to regular classes last year 
but after their house was burned they moved with their family to 
another district 
</TEXT>
