<TEXT>
church and temple bells tolled in nagasaki as 
thousands of people stopped in the streets tuesday to remember the 
moment 43 years ago when the united states dropped an atomic bomb 
on the japanese city 
the citys mayor urged the government to clarify whether us 
ships are bringing nuclear weapons into japan 
at 1102 am the moment when the bomb exploded in a burst of 
blinding light bells tolled as many people on the streets and in 
shopping centers paused for a minute of silence 
nagasaki became the target of the worlds second atomic attack 
on aug 9 1945 the united states dropped the first atomic bomb on 
hiroshima three days earlier japan surrendered about a week later 
to end world war ii 
at peace park near the point where the bomb exploded about 
20000 people gathered for an annual service under a hot sun 
people poured water over a memorial tablet to recall the cries of 
victims suffering from thirst and burns 
families presented a list of 2295 names of bomb victims who 
died during the past year bringing to 77462 the number of 
postwar victims of nuclear radiation their names are inscribed on 
a vault near the parks peace statue 
in the evening about 2000 roman catholics with candles walked 
through areas of the city once destroyed by the bombing a church 
official said 
officials estimate up to 70000 people died immediately from the 
explosion and the accompanying fire storms and radiation about 
70000 residents still suffer from side effects of the plutonium 
bomb doctors and social workers say 
in the bombing of hiroshima an estimated 70000 to 140000 
people died about 350000 people in japan hold certificates 
showing they were victims of the atomic bombings in the two cities 
since the war japan has followed a policy of three nonnuclear 
principles no possession manufacture or introduction into the 
country of nuclear weapons 
speaking at the ceremony in peace park nagasaki mayor hitoshi 
motoshima criticized his government for allowing us ships to dock 
in japan without verifying whether they carry nuclear weapons 
the japanese government should independently check whether 
us ships are carrying nuclear weapons when they call on japanese 
ports and make clear that it still is observing the three 
nonnuclear principles motoshima said 
the nagasaki bombing destroyed almost everything within a radius 
of more than half a mile including 1326 buildings and homes it 
also demolished 23500 homes and buildings outside that radius 
according to a report by the city 
the ancient port city of 450000 has been rebuilt with modern 
office towers and treelined avenues replacing the rubblestrewn 
landscape 
