<TEXT>
the teenage years are troubled times when 
many young people drink too much eat badly are prone to injury 
and violence and often consider suicide according to a survey 
released tuesday 
the data confirmed what many parents and counselors have long 
known or suspected the adolescent years can be dangerous 
dr robert e windom assistant health secretary and head of the 
public health service called the results somewhat dismaying 
the results give us fresh insight concerning what our nations 
teenagers know and how they act concerning health and sexrelated 
issues but they also show that too many young people even when 
they know better dont always make the right health decisions 
windom said in a statement 
the survey sponsored by health education groups and the 
department of health and human services polled 11000 
eighthgraders and 10thgraders during the fall of 1987 from a 
nationally representative sample of 217 public and private schools 
the margin of error was plus or minus 2 to 5 percentage points 
depending on the frequency of the behavior reported officials said 
in one of the more startling findings the study reported that 
26 percent of the eighthgraders and 38 percent of the 10thgraders 
said they had had five or more drinks on one occasion during the 
two weeks preceding the survey 
also 42 percent of the girls and 25 percent of the boys 
surveyed said they have seriously thought about committing 
suicide at some time in their lives nearly one in five girls and 
one in 10 boys of the total surveyed said they had actually tried 
to commit suicide 
w james popham president of iox assessment associates which 
conducted the survey said it was possible some teenagers 
exaggerated their responses but that the results were still 
frightening even if the figures were off by half 
i dont think they are off he said i really think a lot 
of kids in their modest way say its not worth it theres a 
consistent pattern of hopelessness of depression in some of the 
responses 
in the area of health the survey indicated that most teens 
understand that acquired immune deficiency syndrome or aids is 
transmitted by sexual intercourse and drug needles 
they also know that condoms are effective in helping avoid aids 
and believe they should be used but about half of the students 
were unsure or mistakenly believed that washing after sex reduces 
the chances of being infected 
the teens displayed ignorance about other sexually transmitted 
diseases the survey noted that 25 million teenagers are infected 
with such diseases each year and that many teens cannot identify 
common early signs of the infections 
a majority of those surveyed do not know that taking birth 
control pills is ineffective in avoiding these diseases more than 
a third said they would not know where to go for medical care if 
they caught a sexually transmitted disease 
the survey showed that many teens dont eat right even when they 
know they should nearly four of every 10 students said they eat 
fried foods four or more times a week the average student ate 
three snacks a day that were high in fat or sugar and 73 percent 
said they knew that eating such food may be related to heart 
problems or high blood pressure 
sixtyone percent of the girls and 28 percent of the boys said 
they had dieted during the past year and about half of the 
students who dieted used unsafe methods such as fasting others 
tried diet pills laxatives or vomiting 
unintentional injuries are the leading cause of death among 
people aged 15 to 25 with motor vehicle accidents accounting for 
more than 70 percent of accidental deaths the survey showed that a 
substantial portion of teenagers do not guard against such 
injuries 
about 56 percent of those surveyed said they did not wear a seat 
belt the last time they rode in a vehicle about 44 percent of 
10thgraders and 32 percent of eighthgraders said they had ridden 
during the past month with a driver who had used drugs or alcohol 
when they ride bicycles or motorcycles according to the survey 92 
percent said they never wear a protective helmet 
about half the boys and onefourth of the girls reported having 
been involved in at least one fight during the year preceding the 
survey nearly one in five girls reported that during the past year 
while outside of school someone tried to force them to have sex 
about onefourth of the boys said they have carried a knife to 
school at least once during the past year seven percent said they 
did so on a regular basis 
</TEXT>
