<TEXT>
a federal judge who was chastised by a 
higher court for showing bias in favor of ku klux klansmen in a 
race violence case has offered to ban himself from litigation 
involving the federal government 
but so far us district judge william m acker jr 60 has 
not drawn any public call for such blanket disqualification 
acker appointed to the bench by president reagan in 1982 
scheduled a hearing on the issue for friday 
us attorney frank donaldson on tuesday filed a response on 
behalf of the government in which he said the united states has 
at this time insufficient information to determine and no reason to 
believe that judge ackers proposed general recusal is either 
necessary or appropriate 
donaldson who said the justice department will not be 
represented at the hearing said it is the governments view that 
the matter of recusal is better left for consideration on a 
casebycase basis 
ackers rulings against the justice department in the klan 
litigation prompted the 11th us circuit court of appeals to 
remove him from the case in a bluntly worded order 
during the course of this litigation wrote 11th circuit 
judge frank m johnson of montgomery judge ackers position has 
become hardened against the government and he has evidenced a 
commitment that clearly reflects that he is no longer able to view 
these cases impartially 
acker had ruled that the actions of several klansmen accused of 
violating the civil rights of marchers in a violent confrontation 
