<TEXT>
mohammed ali hamadi confessed 
tuesday he helped hijack a twa jetliner to beirut in 1985 but said 
he is not ready to do something like that again and denied he 
killed the us navy diver aboard 
in a statement read in court hamadi said the four hijackers 
were trying to force the release of lebanese shiite moslems 
imprisoned in israel shortly after the ordeal was over israel 
released approximately 700 shiites 
the decision to hijack the plane came after everything else 
failed hamadi said in his surprise confession there was no 
other way to free the prisoners other than the means chosen 
thirtynine americans were held captive for 17 days and us 
navy diver robert stethem was killed his body was thrown onto a 
beirut airport runway 
hamadi is being tried on charges of air piracy and murder in the 
june 1985 twa hijacking the us government also has indicted 
hamadi on charges of air piracy and murder 
hamadi denounced israel for illegal conduct in lebanon 
condemned the united states and said another hijacker had killed 
stethem one of hamadis lawyers said hamadi felt sorry for 
everyone who suffered harm 
in reflecting on the hijacking hamadi told the court i am 
not ready to do something like that again 
as i took part in the action that happened out of the belief 
that there was no other way to get the release of those imprisoned 
now im of the opinion that thats not the case hamadi said 
under west german law hamadi can be convicted of murder even if 
he did not actually fire the shots that killed stethem but one of 
his lawyers said the court would have to prove the hijackers plans 
might have included possible murder 
the court can convict him as a participant in the murder but 
it has to prove that he knew what he was doing said gabrielle 
steckbromme 
three other hijacking suspects remain at large 
hamadi cleanshaven in an openneck shirt read calmly and 
clearly for about 45 minutes while richard and patricia stethem 
parents of the slain diver listened attentively to an interpreter 
the stethems from waldorf md made no gestures visible to 
reporters through the bulletproof glass that separates them from 
hamadi the judges and the rest of the court 
if this act which i committed is against the law then it is a 
result of illegal conduct on the part of israel said hamadi he 
said the hijackers picked a us aircraft because the united 
states is the greatest ally and supporter of israel 
hamadi said that hassan izaldin was in charge of the hijacking 
and had been demanding a negotiator before shooting stethem 
the pistol was in his izaldins hand hamadi said i 
didnt use it our orders were not to harm anyone but i couldnt 
convince him not to shoot 
mrs steckbromme was asked how hamadi felt about the stethems 
presence in court 
he feels sorry for everyone who suffered harm through the 
hijacking mrs steckbromme said 
the lawyer noted that hamadis age at the time of the hijacking 
remains at issue and could determine whether the court will treat 
him as a juvenile young adult or an adult 
but even if the court determines he was a juvenile it could 
decide to sentence him as an adult and hand down a maximum life 
sentence 
the judge asked hamadi to ask his parents to come from lebanon 
to testify about his age then recessed the trial until sept 6 
michael senz another of hamadis lawyers said he hoped the 
confession would lead to more lenient treatment 
the court could now decide not to summon all american 
witnesses because no identification is necessary senz said 
west german television speculated that hamadis confession could 
lead to speedy release of a west german hostage in lebanon but 
government and foreign ministry spokesmen said they had no 
information about any release 
one west german alfred schmidt was released in september 1987 
but the second rudolf cordes remains a hostage 
cordes is believed to be held by hezbollah a radical 
iranianbacked shiite moslem group thought to be holding other 
western hostages in lebanon 
