<TEXT>
a government mission charged with 
extracting new loans from foreign commercial banks begins its 
difficult task this week amid venezuelas growing frustration at 
its inability to escape from its vicious circle of foreign debt 
the team headed by finance minister hector hurtado navarro 
will try to convince banks in new york washington and san 
francisco to lend up to 3 billion to cover this years estimated 
25 billion balance of payments deficit 
the discussions could be rocky as venezuela blames its 
inability to grow out of its economic problems on the weight of the 
foreign debt while foreign banks see its problem as one of lax 
domestic policy 
we understand that the debt is the gordian knot of our current 
economic situation and we have decided to cut it president 
jaime lusinchi stated emphatically in a televised address last week 
the balance of payments deficit is the product of continued low 
oil prices which could limit income from venezuelas main export 
to just 82 billion this year 
scheduled payments on its 34 billion foreign debt estimated at 
5 billion this year will absorb 60 percent of that severely 
limiting the nations prospects for growth in an election year 
but the government is equally frustrated by the fact that 
venezuela paid over 30 billion in capital and interest between 
1983 when its debt problems began and last year but its total 
debt has remained virtually unchanged 
venezuelan officials claim commercial bank creditors have 
reneged on a promise to provide venezuela with new funds and help 
it regain access to international financial markets 
the nations 2034 billion foreign debt refinancing agreement 
first signed in 1986 was revised early in 1987 to allow for more 
favorable terms including a clause in which banks promised to 
look favorably upon requests for new loans 
but besides an estimated 35 billion in shortterm lines of 
credit and a 100 million issue of republic of venezuela bonds no 
new balance of payments loans have been made 
servicing the foreign debt was made under the promise that 
financial flows would be reneweddebt service has been an 
obligation that has limited our possibilities to eradicate our 
crisis lusinchi said 
the frustration has led to persistent rumors in recent weeks 
that venezuela might declare a unilateral debt payment moratorium 
as some government party members want 
but lusinchi and other top administration officials said any 
suspension of payments would occur only if this weeks mission 
fails and even then only in concert with commercial banks 
and hurtado said before leaving for new york last weekend that 
any new talks to seek more favorable terms on the refinanced debt 
would begin only after a new administration takes office early next 
year 
a temporary suspension of payments this year is a faroff 
possibility but it is a possibility said domingo maza zavala a 
private economist who advises the government on economic policy 
but government efforts to control the domestic impact of the 
debt are showing signs of strain 
due to lack of sufficient income government spending programs 
designed to promote growth have been based on internal debt which 
has risen to 7 percent of gross domestic product according to the 
international monetary fund 
the spending resulted in domestic growth of 5 percent in 1986 
for the first time in eight years but growth slowed to 3 percent 
last year and according to private estimates could be flat again 
this year 
inflation which the government hoped to limit to 15 percent 
this year already had topped 12 percent through july and private 
economists estimate it could reach 25 percent by december 
and the free market exchange rate for the us dollar an 
important indicator of local business psychology zoomed last week 
to more than 38 bolivars a record level and nearly three times the 
official exchange rate 
nevertheless analysts feel the government has room to adopt 
policies which would help solve the domestic imbalances including 
raising domestic interest rates and increasing fiscal revenues from 
public services 
the financial mission is armed with an outline of possible steps 
the government could take in return for new cash 
foreign bankers say they probably would require such measures 
which would be similar to austerity guidelines often recommended by 
the imf as a condition of any new loans 
foreign bankers also say venezuela should look for new money in 
other places first which usually means the imf 
but venezuela is unlikely to want to change its policy of 
avoiding an imf connection in order to maintain the freedom to set 
its own economic priorities 
politically for a government ending its term and in an 
electoral year going to the imf would be very very difficult 
said maza zavala 
</TEXT>
