<TEXT>
here are major events leading to mondays 
approval of a joint operating agreement for the detroit news and 
detroit free press 
may 9 1986 the free press and news apply to the justice 
department for a limited antitrust exemption allowing a 
costcutting combination of advertising circulation and business 
operations while news and editorial departments remain separate 
july 23 1986 the justice departments antitrust division 
recommends that attorney general edwin meese ii order a public 
hearing saying the papers have not proved the need for a joa 
aug 22 1986 a deadline for public comment is extended after 
mayor coleman young unions representing newspaper employees and 
some members of congress call for public hearings 
feb 25 1987 meese says he will appoint an administrative law 
judge to conduct a hearing 
may 29 1987 young and five unions obtain 30000 pages of 
documents from the newspapers detailing costcutting efforts loss 
projections and other items 
june 1 1987 the free press and news file written testimony 
saying the free press lost 17 million in 1986 the news lost 127 
million and cost cuts or price increases would not save the free 
press 
june 30 1987 the challengers submit exhibits and testimony 
that the free press does not meet the test of a failing newspaper 
aug 3 1987 administrative law judge morton needelman begins a 
hearing in detroit 
aug 10 1987 gannett co inc chairman allen neuharth 
testifies that the news will spend whatever is necessary to defeat 
the free press if a joa is denied 
aug 12 1987 knightridder inc chairman alvah h chapman jr 
testifies that he will recommend closing the free press if a joa is 
denied the hearing ends aug 24 
sept 23 1987 the justice departments antitrust division 
again recommends rejection of a joa saying the papers failed to 
prove the free press is failing 
dec 29 1987 needelman recommends that meese reject the joa 
jan 10 1988 i am worried the free press could die free 
press publisher david lawrence writes in a frontpage column he 
asks readers to write hundreds respond the paper runs excerpts 
unions call the column a corporate propaganda advertisement 
mouthing the knightridder line 
jan 21 1988 the knightridder board votes to close the free 
press if a joa is denied 
feb 7 1988 a mailers union drops its opposition to the joa in 
return for job protection buyouts and severance pay 
feb 11 1988 young drops his opposition saying a joa is 
better than a onenewspaper town 
feb 15 1988 unions representing press workers drop opposition 
to the joa 
feb 16 1988 officers of teamsters local 372 the largest 
union and unions representing typographers and photoengravers drop 
their opposition leaving the newspaper guild of detroit and the 
antitrust division as the remaining opponents 
july 25 1988 the newspaper guild local 22 drops its opposition 
to the joa 
aug 8 1988 meese approves the joa 
