<TEXT>
investors dumped stocks and bonds tuesday but 
the dollar rallied smartly against major foreign currencies after 
the federal reserve boosted its key bank lending rate a half 
percentage point for the first time since black monday 
the increase in the discount rate to 65 percent from 6 
percent was made to reduce inflationary pressures and in 
light of the growing spread of market interest rates over the 
discount rate according to the fed 
many economists predicted other interest rates including those 
on mortgages or homeequity loans would rise as a result of the 
feds credit tightening and a few market watchers worried about 
the nearterm effects on the already skittish stock market 
the increase in the discountrate the fee the central bank 
charges member banks for loans was the second since alan 
greenspan replaced paul a volcker at the feds helm a year ago on 
sept 4 the central bank raised the rate for the first time in 
three years to 6 percent from 55 percent 
while last septembers increase in the rate also was taken in 
response to inflationary fears analysts later cited it as a 
contributing factor to the oct 19 stock market crash 
i just hope history doesnt repeat itself said irwin 
kellner chief economist for manufacturers hanover trust co i 
dont look for a market collapse but the crosscurrents of the 
stock market arent very favorable it certainly is dangerous 
on wall street stock prices fell sharply in response to the 
announcement with the dow jones average of 30 industrials losing 
slightly more than 28 points to 207913 it had been down nearly 
40 points late in the day 
bond prices tumbled while interest rates rose the treasurys 
bellwether 30year issue was off about 10 per 1000 face amount 
while its yield jumped to 919 percent from 910 percent late 
monday 
in foreign exchange the dollar advanced strongly against major 
currencies higher interest rates make the dollar more valuable 
the biggest increases came against the japanese yen and west 
german marks by late afternoon tuesday the dollar had broken 
through the psychologically important 135yen level from mondays 
new york close of 13397 and to 192 marks from 190 
analysts had expected the fed to tighten its reins on the money 
supply this week but few were expecting an increase in the 
discount rate which is the most dramatic move the fed can take 
tuesdays increase brings the discount rate to its steepest 
level since april 1986 when it fell to 65 percent from 7 percent 
the credit markets have been screaming for a discount rate 
increase for quite some time the surprise was in the timing of 
it said kellner 
not only is the republican convention coming up but were in 
the middle of a treasury refunding in which the government is 
auctioning off 22 billion in new three and 10year notes this 
week to pay off its old debts 
i dont think inflation is any worse today than it was last 
year said kellner 
but robert a brusca chief financial economist for nikko 
securities co international inc defended the discount rate hike 
the economy has been doing well but inflation has ben creeping 
up he said its the feds job to throw cold water on the 
economy when it starts overheating and thats what it appears to be 
doing right now 
among the recent signs of strength in the economy was the july 
unemployment rate which at 54 percent was near its 14year lows 
concerns about inflation have pushed interest rates higher in 
recent months the federal funds rate which is the interest on 
overnight loans between banks has been on the rise elizabeth g 
reiners an economist at dean witter reynolds inc said the yield 
spread between the fed funds rate and discount rate had been at its 
highest level in about a year 
a month ago major banks boosted their prime lending rates a 
half percentage point to 95 percent from 9 percent 
i wouldnt be surprised if we had another prime rate hike by 
friday said david resler chief economist nomura securities inc 
