trading tuesday on the new york stock exchange 
the lawsuit claims that in the three days after the ad was 
published gillette received 642000 proxies revoking prior ballots 
submitted for coniston the difference would have closed a 52 
percent to 48 percent gap but not reversed the outcome 
the suit represents people who lost money selling gillette stock 
between april 19 the date of the advertisements and july 6 when 
wolf ruled that the ads contained false and misleading 
information about coniston 
the ads which appeared in the new york times and the wall 
street journal said coniston was controlled by a complicated 
web of foreign and domestic firms involved in its effort to 
control gillette 
