<TEXT>
a federal maritime commission finding that 
industry rules for containerized ships unfairly discriminate 
against small cargo shippers was upheld tuesday by a federal 
appeals court 
the us circuit court of appeals here said the maritime 
commission correctly ignored the rules effect on labormanagement 
relations when it found they improperly forced small shippers to 
employ unionized dock workers to handle their cargo 
it is not the national labor policy to allow otherwise 
unlawful activity merely because an employer and a union have 
agreed to it in mandatory collective bargaining a threejudge 
panel of the court said in a unanimous ruling 
at issue are rules first negotiated in 1968 by the international 
longshoremens association and the shipping industry that require 
unionized dockhands to load or unload cargo containers that pass 
through east coast ports 
the rules exempt manufacturers and large shippers that load 
cargo into containers at their own warehouses 
but small shippers whose cargo would not fill a single 
container are forced to lease containers from the shipping 
companies and deliver their goods for loading at a unionized pier 
the regulations were negotiated as part of the industrys 
efforts to introduce cargo containers which can be unloaded from a 
ship into a railroad car or a flatbed truck without being opened 
by dock hands 
the widespread use of containers has greatly reduced the number 
of longshoremen needed to unload ships and the rules were 
implemented to help the ila cut the losses to its workforce 
last year the maritime commission unanimously struck down the 
regulations which were challenged by freight forwarders trucking 
companies and handlers of small amounts of cargo 
the commissions finding however was stayed while the ila and 
the shipping industry appealed the decision 
john hammon executive vice president of the national customs 
brokers and forwarders association of america inc hailed the 
courts decision saying the rules amount to flagrant 
featherbeading that was just very damaging to importexport 
commerce 
there was on immediate comment from the ila which is expected 
to appeal the decision to the supreme court 
the ruling could also become a bargaining chip in contract 
negotiations between the ila and the shipping industry 
the regulations require that merchandise placed on containers 
within 50 miles of a port by nonila workers had to be unloaded on 
the dock and placed into different containers before it was loaded 
on ships 
the rules mean extra costs in delays and exposure to 
pilferage hammon said small cargo shippers have begun using 
canadian ports to avoid the restrictions resulting in less 
business for east coast ports he said 
</TEXT>
