a report from the respected chicagobased crop analyst conrad 
leslie generated buying interest in crop futures 
leslie estimated 1988 us soybean production at 148 billion 
bushels down 23 percent from last years actual production of 191 
billion bushels and corn production at 428 billion bushels a 39 
percent drop from the 706 billion bushels harvested last year 
this means the worst drought of the century is producing the 
smallest us corn crop since 1970 leslie said in his report 
leslie also reported signs of spider mite damage to soybean 
plants in illinois and iowa even if such plants received rain he 
said they may only stabili the contract for 
delivery in september at 379 a bushel corn was 1 cent to 4 
cents higher with september at 299 a bushel oats were 1 cent to 
5 cents lower with september at 268 a bushel and soybeans were 
3 cents to 20 cents higher with august at 855 a bushel 
coffee futures prices surged in light trading on new yorks 
coffee sugar amp cocoa exchange but analysts said the rally was 
technical in nature and not related to any new developments within 
the international coffee organization 
light buying by coffee roasters nudged prices past a key 
technical point which triggered a broader rally said sandra kaul 
coffee analyst in new york with shearson lehman hutton inc 
coffee for september delivery settled 381 cents higher at 
11834 a pound 
gold and silver futures retreated on new yorks commodity 
exchange after the federal reserve board announced it was boosting 
the discount rate from 6 percent to 65 percent 
but richard levine vice president of the precious metals and 
foreign exchange group at elders futures inc in new york said the 
selloff was precipitated by weak technical factors not by 
prospects of lower inflation 
shortterm technicals were bearish before the fed had anything 
to say he said 
gold settled 280 to 3 lower with august at 42740 a troy 
ounce silver was 85 cents to 88 cents lower with september at 
663 a troy ounce 
cattle futures finished mixed on the chicago mercantile exchange 
amid conflicting views about future beef demand and cash prices 
analysts said pork futures retreated on weakening cash prices 
