<DOCNO> AP880809-0255 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the partial merger of two detroit newspapers may not have an 
immediate impact across the industry analysts say but it could 
set the tone for the future with the market becoming more 
concentrated and the wealthiest media companies growing more 
powerful 
the deal approved this week by us attorney general edwin meese 
iii brings together gannett co inc owner of the detroit news 
and knightridder inc owner of the detroit free press in a deal 
four times larger than any joint operating agreement approved under 
the newspaper preservation act of 1970 
while the move is designed to preserve two independent editorial 
voices in a big metropolitan market some analysts and scholars 
still raise questions about the moves competitive impact 
critics charge the detroit combination is a step toward further 
concentration of the industry where the trend is toward chain 
ownership and media conglomerates and where the number of 
independently owned papers is fading 
this means that eventually there will be no city in the 
country left with competing papers and then pressure will be more 
immediate to wipe out the little competition thats left in the 
form of alternative papers community papers and suburban papers 
said bruce b brugmann publisher of the san francisco bay guardian 
william keating chief executive officer of the detroit 
newspaper agency that will oversee the merger believes joint 
operating arrangements make good economic sense in an industry 
where second place often leads to financial failure 
in the detroit case the advertising market share where a 
newspaper gets the bulk of its revenue had become so heavily 
weighted in favor of the detroit news that the free press couldnt 
survive keating said 
he said joint operating arrangements will continue to benefit 
the industry by saving newspapers too weak to survive on their own 
some newspapers will be saved by reason of a joint operating 
agreement said keating 
the danger in concentration however is that it could dilute 
competition by shifting power from the readers to media owners who 
are in the position to charge higher prices for circulation and 
advertising 
all we really know is that prices are going to go up said 
stephen lacy professor at michigan state university who has 
studied joint newspaper agreements and approves of the detroit 
arrangement 
theyll be cutting their costs and increasing their revenues 
its the same thing that happens in any monopoly situation lacy 
said 
lacy predicted that detroit newsstand prices now among the 
lowest in the nation at between 15 cents and 20 cents per copy 
could be raised to the industry average of 35 cents within the next 
few years 
alan lenhoff spokesman for the detroit free press indicated 
tuesday that prices will go up but would not say when or by how 
much 
what you have in detroit are among the lowest newspaper 
circulation prices and advertising rates in the country lenhoff 
said both have been losing approximately 30 million a year 
logic would tell you that some changes are coming but it has not 
been announced to what extent 
lenhoff said an announcement may be forthcoming before the 
merger takes effect on aug 19 
in 1920 700 cities had competing dailies today there are 22 
eighty percent of daily circulation is controlled by chains and 
chains have begun to merge with each other 
gannett who has absorbed other chains in recent years is not a 
newcomer to joint newspaper agreements the company is now an owner 
in eight of the 20 joint contracts and knightridder is an owner in 
three 
under the partial merger approved monday the detroit 
newspapers among the 10 largest in the country will merge 
production advertising and circulation departments for 100 years 
while maintaining separate editorial and news departments 
although such a merger is illegal for other businesses under 
antitrust law the 1970 newspaper preservation act granted 
newspapers selective exemption from the law if one of the 
newspapers is failing financially the legislative intent was to 
preserve an editorial voice where one otherwise might be lost 
some analysts say the detroit case could set a precedent for 
other large metropolitan newspapers but others say there are few 
cities with competing papers ripe for such a merger 
of the 22 cities with separately owned competing dailies only 
a handful are potential candidates for joint agreements including 
denver dallas chicago and boston 
there are so few markets where people would even want to get 
together and talk about it lacy said 
</TEXT>
